  "author": "SiteFlow Operations Team",
  "publishDate": "2026-05-08T19:10:16+00:00",
  "body": "\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-ad1aa788a7c463194418ce08ec55ff0d wp-block-paragraph\">How to set the number of decimal places used for currency amounts and quantities across all documents in your company. This setting controls how numbers display on invoices, purchase orders, BOQs, material records, and reports throughout SiteFlow.</p>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-8b579f97c281b6a0e88fc50ff4c2bc9b\">Prerequisites</h2>\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-9e0c2b72fb53170fdf8ea1867a2afc9a\">\n<li>You need Admin access</li>\n<li>Decide on your decimal preferences before the team starts creating documents. Changing this setting mid-project changes how new entries display but does not recalculate previously saved records.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-446807853f25a8805c6ca3afb17c1048\">Step 1: Go to Settings</h2>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-af211e30a7d126690952b419306821e5 wp-block-paragraph\">Click Setting in the left sidebar.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-52771\" decoding=\"async\" height=\"448\" src=\"/images/recon/2-2-1-1024x448.webp\" width=\"1024\"/></figure>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-e4ec717af7d594a0d9f1eeba30251853\">Step 2: Open Decimal Settings</h2>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-ebd4affb91c4c7d2bf0949b4a91f48b0 wp-block-paragraph\">Click Decimal Settings from the Settings menu.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-52772\" decoding=\"async\" height=\"448\" src=\"/images/recon/3-4-1024x448.webp\" width=\"1024\"/></figure>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-9c296c3e7df0adaecafe363cb1d05db7\">Step 3: Set Currency Decimal Places</h2>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-913aaefbeb0543349a43c513e4598cf4 wp-block-paragraph\">Under <strong>Company Decimal Setting</strong>, find the <strong>Currency Decimal Places</strong> field.</p>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-5bfb28cf989c4e3b004a7714f9043760 wp-block-paragraph\">This controls how many decimal places appear on all monetary amounts across the platform — invoices, purchase orders, expense entries, payment records, BOQ values, and financial reports.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table is-style-stripes\"><table class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color has-border-color has-palette-color-1-border-color has-fixed-layout\" style=\"border-width:2px\"><thead><tr><th>Value</th><th>How Amounts Display</th><th>When to Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>0</strong></td><td>Rs 10,000</td><td>When your company works in whole rupee amounts only</td></tr><tr><td><strong>2</strong></td><td>Rs 10,000.50</td><td>Standard for most Indian businesses (default)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>3</strong></td><td>Rs 10,000.500</td><td>When working with currencies or rates that require three decimal precision</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-52773\" decoding=\"async\" height=\"448\" src=\"/images/recon/4-3-1024x448.webp\" width=\"1024\"/></figure>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-003da45b590c7651dd13fc0e04f909e4 wp-block-paragraph\">Click the field and enter your preferred value.</p>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-79a31d1cf6e70afcfceec1a60aafd985\">Step 4: Set Quantity Decimal Places</h2>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-3927f94f118a47a3f2fc0f1beef7c303 wp-block-paragraph\">Find the <strong>Quantity Decimal Places</strong> field.</p>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-bcada519a34a9834f413cdc35d755f0c wp-block-paragraph\">This controls how many decimal places appear for material quantities, measurements, and units across purchase orders, GRNs, BOQ quantities, material usage records, and inventory.</p>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table is-style-stripes\"><table class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color has-border-color has-palette-color-1-border-color has-fixed-layout\" style=\"border-width:2px\"><thead><tr><th>Value</th><th>How Quantities Display</th><th>When to Use</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>0</strong></td><td>10 kg</td><td>When your team works only in whole unit quantities</td></tr><tr><td><strong>2</strong></td><td>10.50 kg</td><td>For standard quantity precision</td></tr><tr><td><strong>3</strong></td><td>10.500 kg</td><td>When materials are measured in precise fractions (default)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>4</strong></td><td>10.5000 kg</td><td>For high-precision material tracking (lab, pharma, specialty work)</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-52775\" decoding=\"async\" height=\"448\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"/images/recon/5-2-1024x448.webp\" width=\"1024\"/></figure>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-af60467445bfcdef614c2d14249a96e0 wp-block-paragraph\">Click the field and enter your preferred value.</p>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-0c6bbeaef52cb814ef6c835a37403e90\">Step 5: Save</h2>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-01f426de99ef50732d644f0089db1dcd wp-block-paragraph\">Click <strong>Save</strong> to apply both settings.</p>\n<p class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-b841d61c7634255b2c99f5fce25a8b38 wp-block-paragraph\">The changes take effect immediately across the platform. Reload the app if existing documents still show the old format.</p>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-medium-font-size\">How This Setting Affects Different Parts of SiteFlow</h2>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table is-style-stripes\"><table class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color has-border-color has-palette-color-1-border-color has-fixed-layout\" style=\"border-width:2px\"><thead><tr><th>Area</th><th>What Changes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Sales Invoices</td><td>Line item amounts and totals display with the new currency decimal places</td></tr><tr><td>Purchase Orders</td><td>Item unit rates, quantities, and totals reflect both settings</td></tr><tr><td>BOQ / Estimate</td><td>Item quantities use quantity decimal places; item rates and values use currency decimal places</td></tr><tr><td>Material Records</td><td>GRN quantities, material usage, and stock levels display with quantity decimal places</td></tr><tr><td>Expense and Payment entries</td><td>All amounts display with currency decimal places</td></tr><tr><td>Reports</td><td>All quantity and currency columns reflect the updated settings</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-medium-font-size\">Tips</h2>\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-f828435e5ef13cc8c1f8b8bf7aa493fa\">\n<li>Set decimal places before the team starts creating documents. Changing the setting later updates how new numbers display, but previously saved entries keep their original stored values. The display format updates but the underlying number does not change.</li>\n<li>For most Indian construction companies, the default settings work well: 2 decimal places for currency (matching standard rupee invoicing) and 3 for quantities (covering materials measured in kilograms, litres, or metres with fractional values).</li>\n<li>Infrastructure and road projects that track materials like bitumen or cement in tonnes often benefit from 3 quantity decimal places to correctly display values like 14.750 MT.</li>\n<li>Interior and fit-out companies using supply-and-install BOQs with per-sqft rates may find 2 currency decimal places sufficient since rates rarely go beyond paise.</li>\n<li>If your team reports that quantities are getting cut off or rounded unexpectedly on documents, increase the quantity decimal places by one and save.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color wp-elements-604b961fc912f969ba9505600f05f890\">If Something Goes Wrong</h2>\n<figure class=\"wp-block-table is-style-stripes\"><table class=\"has-palette-color-4-color has-text-color has-link-color has-border-color has-palette-color-1-border-color has-fixed-layout\" style=\"border-width:2px\"><thead><tr><th>Problem</th><th>Likely Cause</th><th>What to Do</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Cannot see Decimal Settings</td><td>Not an Admin</td><td>Ask your Admin to configure the settings or grant Admin access</td></tr><tr><td>Numbers still showing old decimal format after saving</td><td>App not refreshed</td><td>Reload the browser or mobile app fully after saving</td></tr><tr><td>Quantities showing as whole numbers despite setting decimals</td><td>Setting saved but cache not cleared</td><td>Log out and log back in, then check again</td></tr><tr><td>Invoice totals look different after changing decimal places</td><td>Display rounding changed</td><td>The stored value is unchanged. The visual rounding has updated to match the new setting. Verify with your accounts team if concerned.</td></tr><tr><td>Cannot enter more than a certain number of decimal places in a field</td><td>Field input cap</td><td>The field accepts up to the number set in Decimal Settings. If you need more precision, increase the setting and save first.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>\n<div aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"wp-block-spacer\" style=\"height:100px\"></div>\n<p class=\"wp-block-paragraph\"></p>\n"
}